Ukraine's offensive to retake the Kherson oblast could generate many more refugees. Many might be forcibly relocated by Russia to distant regions of Russia (Siberia!), as with the case of Mariupol. Already Russia is processing many inhabitants through its "filtration" system in which people are stripped naked, many tortured, everyone's cell phones searched, and those who aren't imprisoned or executed are deported to low population and distant areas of Russia. This ongoing horror is a huge motivation for Ukraine to expel Russians from this region, and for those who fear filtration to flee to areas held by Ukraine by any means possible. Given the partisan warfare ongoing behind the front lines, there is a good chance many will be enabled to escape across the front liens. These people will not be counted for this question, only the deported victims of filtration.
As of today, it surpassed the lower threshold but are not likely to do so with the upper threshold
More than 8.8
Russian offensives in Kharviv, Donbass means residents of these areas will continue to leave.

Just had the thought... I think I read that numbers don't track return trips, so potentially people who leave, return and then leave again AS WELL AS relief workers and volunteers that arrive and leave factor into this final tally. >8.8 is very likely, but I can see it being close too.

Currently 8,402,336 as of June 28, for a total of 56k/day during that period. In order to hit 8.8m by the 15th, we need to exceed 23,392, so I am completely reversing my forecast.

Just under 50k refugees are crossing the border per day and that has been remarkably consistent for the last 90 days. What isn't known is if people return to Ukraine how is that counted? Also, if they return again to, say, Poland. So there may be a number of people who travel somewhat consistently but are regarded as basically clones. In a way that doesn't matter but it isn't what the question is counting but it's irksome.

There are 17 days left in the forecast period. As of 2022-06-28, there has been 8,402,336 border crossings from Ukraine (since 24 February 2022). Over the past 30 days there has been an average of 51,970 border crossing from Ukraine / day with a standard deviation of 6,012. Based on 100,000 Monte Carlo runs this gives a range of 9.2 to 9.4 million border crossings from Ukraine by July 15, 2022.

Last update from June 28th: 8,402,336 refugees have fled Ukraine so far. The previous week rate was approximately 50,000 people a day - that would mean it is likely the fourth bracket will be attained in 8 days, and there is 17 days left. Feels like a safe bet to me.

We would need 400k more to surpass 8.8M total – a substantial drop from the current 45-50k/day down to <25k/day. This does not look realistic to me.

Ok, realistically, it'll be bin 4. 8.0M on June 21 + 0.3M added June 21-28 = 8.3M on June 28, conservatively. It's hard to see how another 0.5M wouldn't be added over the next 2.4 weeks after that.

8.007M total as of June 21 and 7.619M as of June 14, so 0.388M were added in the week from June 14 to 21. There are 3.4 weeks of data left in the forecast period. 8.007M + (3.4 weeks x 0.388M/week) = 8.007M + 1.319M = 9.326M. Bin 4 looks increasingly likely.

Only 3 weeks left, it seems unlikely there will be a spike in crossings to take the total number above 8.8 million. Hopefully Western supplies of more advanced weaponry will make their way to the frontline.

June 14 update: 7.514M. Up 0.243M from 7.271M on June 7. This is the lowest weekly rate in a long time. (I'm not sure how long.)32 days = 4.57 weeks from June 13 to July 15.7.514M + 4.57 weeks * 0.243M/week = 8.6M.So I'm increasing my forecast on bin 3 vs. bin 4.

In order for us to fall below 8.8m, we'd have to fall below 42k per day, and in order to fall below 7.6m we'd have to fall below 10,000. That seems yowza unlikely to me, so I'm going to increase confidence a lot on that middle bucket.

Figures updated as per yesterday: 5,801,159. As pointed out by the likes of @numa_takeda & @alter_hugo, linearity can be assumed within a relatively safe margin of error and daily change, and one can extrapolate a daily increase of roughly 50.000 refugees per day. Concurringly, we have to take into account that refugee figures do not follow the number of internally displaced people (IDP)s in a one-to-one fashion. Importantly, corridors of mobility (including still intact infrastructure) that are fairly proximate to battlegrounds play a primary role, thus pointing towards that refugees being able to flee (flee rate) will start plateauing. This would point towards option C as the most likely scenario. As a part of a broader scenario planning, taking into account the worst battles are yet to come. Things to follow:

The rate is definitely slowing down with about 3.4M in March and about 1.2M so far in April. The shift in focus to eastern Ukraine is now a couple of weeks old and this trend of decreasing rate has held. If this "second derivative" trend holds (i.e. the monthly rate cuts in half again in June and in again in the first half of July, then we would have just over the 6.4 mark by July 15. It seems relatively plausible to me that the rate decreases even faster than that if things settle into a stalemate in the East. So, still leaving a bit more probability in the first bin than the crowd for now. The points I have in bins four and five are basically for my general uncertainty: I would guess that there are major escalatory situations that I am not thinking of and that these have non-negligible probability.
Overall our team assesses that the worst of the fighting and key factors in refugee flow will diminish over the next 85 days.

The flood has slowed, and a few are even returning. Only 0.4M became refugees in the first 2 weeks of April. But I think ongoing Russian military campaigns in the south will keep causing more to leave, if they can. I agree with the crowd that the lower forecast bins are most likely. 4.6M from Feb 24 to April 13, in 1.5 months. 3 months in this forecast. The only way I could picture a similar overall pace would be if the war took a turn towards chemical weapons or tactical nuclear weapons. Barring such developments, I think it's reasonable to guess that we'll most likely see the numbers climb at rates similar to those now (0.4M/2 weeks), so that we might see ~0.5M-1.0M new refugees per month, for a total of ~6.1M-7.6M by July 28. But a lot can change, so I'm casting a wide net. I think the crowd is about right. For the total to stay under 6.4M, only 1.8M would be added, or an average of 0.6M/month. That's quite possible, if the rate keeps falling.

At this point, it's hard to imagine and increase in the flow of refugees fleeing Ukraine. The war has moved its focus on the East, from which most people who wanted to flee to had the ability to do so, will have already done so. Thus, I expect the flow of refugees to start slowing down.

In the most recent fortnight (April 1-15th), 800k refugees had left. If we assume this rate until July 15th, we would have a total number of 4.8m + 0.8m*6 = 9.6m... but there is not an "unlimited supply of refugees"!! First of all we have to guess the initial number of "potential refugees", we have to consider Ukraine total population (42m) and substract men between 18 and 65 (around 14m), people that will not leave because of ideology or health reasons (say 10m), etc. Therefore, we would be estimating 18m as initial number of "potential refugees", of which 4.8m (26.7 %) already have left. What has happened with the remaining 73.3%? They have had 50 days for leaving but so far they have decided to stay (perhaps my guess of people that stay because of ideology or health is too low). My estimation is that an additional 10% of the "initial potential refugees" will leave in the next three months, giving an estimation of 4.8m + (18m * 10%) = 6.6m. There may be an event that triggers more departures (e.g. CBRN weapons). However, this is considered unlikey and current scenario suggests that Russia is focusing in key areas, which means less threatened population that will consider leaving their homes.
The number of refugees leaving is quite steady and not declining (at least in a meaningful way). Were the current rate to continue the number would be just shy of 10m by 15 July.

At this point, most of the Ukrainians who want to leave -- and are able -- have already done so. Those who are left and want to leave are either the trapped, the sick, the elderly, or committed to say for a major reason (family member who can't leave). Beyond that, you have people who are committed to fighting Russia or providing support for to those who fight.
Putin will have to resolve this soon. He cannot sustain this. Because it will have to be resolved, the number of refugees will dwindle.
